# 9ai: Plan 9 C Agent — Design Document

## Scope

Port the pi LLM agent backend to Plan 9 C, exposing it as a 9P file server.
No TUI.  GitHub Copilot provider only (Anthropic Messages wire format — Claude models).
Targets native Plan 9 as the primary platform; plan9port on Linux/macOS also supported.

The name is **9ai** (the 9P service is posted as "9ai").

9ai provides the same class of capabilities as pi's RPC mode — multi-turn
conversation, tool use, streaming output, session persistence, model switching,
steering — but through a 9P file interface.  It has its own file layout, event
format, and session storage.  9ai-acme is a fresh acme integration script that
uses the 9P files directly.

---

## What We Are Building

A standalone program that:

  1. Posts a 9P service ("9ai") into the namespace on startup
  2. Accepts user messages via /message; steering via /steer
  3. Drives a multi-turn agent loop against the Copilot/Anthropic API
  4. Provides the single exec tool (direct execve, no shell)
  5. Streams LLM response text via /output (raw text, blocking reads)
  6. Emits structured events via /event (RS/US-delimited records, blocking reads)
  7. Appends a complete session record to ~/lib/9ai/sessions/<uuid>

---

## Record Format

All structured data in 9ai — the /event stream and session files — uses a
single record format built on two ASCII control characters that exist for
exactly this purpose:

  U+001F  0x1F  INFORMATION SEPARATOR ONE   — field separator (FS)
  U+001E  0x1E  INFORMATION SEPARATOR TWO   — record separator (RS)

A record is a sequence of fields separated by FS, terminated by RS:
  field₀ FS field₁ FS field₂ RS

Fields are verbatim byte strings.  Newlines, tabs, and all other characters
pass through literally.  No escaping is needed for ordinary text.

Literal FS or RS within a field value is represented by doubling:
  0x1F 0x1F → literal 0x1F
  0x1E 0x1E → literal 0x1E

This doubling case is extremely rare in practice (these characters almost
never appear in source code, command output, or prose).  The parser is simple:
scan for 0x1E to find record boundaries, then split on 0x1F for fields, then
collapse doubled separators.

In C:
  #define FS ""
  #define RS ""

  Bprint(b, "text" FS "%s" RS, chunk);
  Bprint(b, "tool_end" FS "ok" FS "%s" RS, full_output);

Human-readable conversion: `tr '' '	
'`

---

## Event Records

The first field of every record is the event type.

Records delivered on /event (agent-side events only):

  turn_start  FS  <session-uuid>  FS  <model>
  thinking    FS  <text>
  text        FS  <text>
  tool_start  FS  <name>  FS  <tool-call-id>  FS  <argv[0]>  FS  <argv[1]>  ...
  tool_end    FS  <ok|err>  FS  <full-output>
  turn_end    FS  <end_turn|aborted|error>
  error       FS  <message>
  model       FS  <new-model-name>
  session_new FS  <new-session-uuid>

Additional records written only to the session file (inputs, not agent events):

  session  FS  <uuid>  FS  <model>  FS  <unix-timestamp>   ← file header record
  prompt   FS  <text>                                       ← user message sent
  steer    FS  <text>                                       ← steering message sent

Notes:
  - tool_start has a variable number of fields: type, name, id, then one field
    per argv element.  No quoting or joining needed; each element is its own field.
  - text and thinking records carry individual delta chunks as they arrive from
    the SSE stream.  On session replay, consecutive text records are concatenated
    to reconstruct the full response.
  - tool_end carries the full exec output — no truncation for the session file.
    For the live /event stream the same full output is delivered.
  - prompt and steer records are NOT emitted on /event; they record inputs and
    belong only in the session file.

