## The exec Tool

### What the LLM sees

One tool declaration, hardcoded as a constant string in the binary:

  {
    "name": "exec",
    "description": "Execute a program directly (no shell). Use standard
      Unix programs for all file operations: cat/head to read,
      grep/find to search, ed/patch/awk/sed to edit, cc/mk to compile.",
    "input_schema": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "argv": {
          "type": "array", "items": {"type":"string"},
          "description": "Program and arguments, e.g. [\"grep\",\"-r\",\"foo\",\"src\"]"
        },
        "stdin": {
          "type": "string",
          "description": "Optional text to supply as stdin."
        }
      },
      "required": ["argv"]
    }
  }

Anthropic Messages format uses "input_schema"; OpenAI Completions format uses "parameters".
The binary emits the appropriate form based on the current model's wire format.

### C implementation

  1. Parse argv[] and optional stdin from accumulated input_json_delta JSON
  2. threadspawn(fd[3], argv[0], argv): fork, wire up stdin/stdout/stderr pipes
  3. If stdin provided: write to child stdin pipe, then close write end
  4. Read stdout+stderr into a capped buffer (512KB; tail on overflow)
  5. waitfor(pid): collect exit status
  6. Return tool_result: output text + "\nexited N" suffix if nonzero

No shell.  threadspawn() handles fork+exec on both Plan 9 (rfork) and plan9port.

On Plan 9: rfork flags include RFNOTEG and RFCNAMEG (clean namespace for child;
RFCNAMEG is ignored on plan9port).

Abort: postnote(pid, "kill") on Plan 9, kill(pid, SIGTERM) on plan9port,
then force-kill after 2s.

