## Session Storage

Session files live at ~/lib/9ai/sessions/<uuid> — plain files, no extension.
Each file is an append-only stream of records in the format described above.

The file is self-describing: the first record is always:
  session  FS  <uuid>  FS  <model>  FS  <unix-timestamp>  RS

Subsequent records are written in order as events occur:
  prompt   FS  <text>                          ← user sends /message
  steer    FS  <text>                          ← user sends /steer
  turn_start  FS  <uuid>  FS  <model>
  thinking FS  <chunk>                         ← one record per delta
  text     FS  <chunk>                         ← one record per delta
  tool_start  FS  <name>  FS  <id>  FS  <argv[0]>  FS  ...
  tool_end FS  <ok|err>  FS  <full-output>
  turn_end FS  <end_turn|aborted|error>
  model    FS  <name>                          ← if model changed mid-session

The session file IS the complete record of the conversation.  No separate
index, no JSON metadata.  Human-readable with `tr '' '	
'`.

### Session replay

On load, the agent proc scans the session file forward:
  - prompt/steer records → user messages in history
  - text records (concatenated between turn_start and turn_end) → assistant response
  - thinking records → thinking blocks (retained for display, not sent to API)
  - tool_start + tool_end pairs → tool call + result in history
  - model records → update current model

The reconstructed history is translated into Anthropic messages format for
the next API request.

### emit_event() and write_session()

The agent proc has two output paths per event:
  emit_event(type, fields...)   → formats record, sends on eventchan (→ /event)
  write_session(type, fields...)→ formats record, appends to session Biobuf

For agent events (turn_start through session_new): both are called.
For input events (prompt, steer): only write_session() is called.

Both use the same field layout; the difference is purely in destination.
The session Biobuf is flushed (Bflush) at turn_end and after tool_end.

### 9ai-sessions companion script

Lists sessions for display in a picker window:

  9ai-sessions [dir]

Reads ~/lib/9ai/sessions/ (or given dir).  For each file, reads the first
record (type must be "session") and the first "prompt" record.
Output: one tab-separated line per session:
  <uuid>  <model>  <date>  <first-prompt-snippet>

